    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-02-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-02-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="262"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760D.61/1157: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grankulla</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Helsinki</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1940-02-21T18:00:00+02:00">February 21, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 22—1:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>108. Minister of Foreign Affairs told me this afternoon that the German
                        Minister<note n="64" xml:id="d262fn64">Wipert von Blücher.</note> who has
                    just returned from visit to Berlin had indicated no change in German attitude
                    towards Finnish conflict with Russia. He had again defined this attitude as one
                    of strict aloofness and disinterest. German Minister had also asked that Finnish
                    Government confirm official German denials that the Russians were using <pb
                        facs="0304" n="292" xml:id="pg_292"/> German technical assistance and war
                    supplies against Finland. Tanner said he had consented to do this and an
                    authorized statement accordingly appeared in local press today to the effect
                    that reports published abroad have not been verified that German officers are
                    assisting Russians in operations against Finland and that Russians have been
                    using German implements of war. German Minister apparently explained again that
                    pact with Soviet Russia had been necessary for Germany to avoid having to wage
                    war on two fronts.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>[<hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
